{"cursor":"13588","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox language |name = Common Brittonic |region = Great Britain south of the\nFirth of Forth. |extinct= Developed into Old Welsh, Cumbric, Cornish and Breton\nby AD 600 |familycolor = Indo-European |fam2 = Celtic |fam3 = Insular\nCeltic |fam4 = Brythonic |iso3 = none |linglist = 1bd |lingua = 50-AB }} 'Common\nBrittonic' (also called 'Common Brythonic', 'British', 'Old Brythonic', or 'Old\nBrittonic') was an ancient P-Celtic language spoken in Britain. It was the\nlanguage of the Celtic people known as the Britons, and by the 6th century it\nsplit into the various Brythonic languages: Welsh, Cumbric, Cornish, and Breton.\nIt is classified as a P-Celtic and Insular Celtic language.\n\nCommon Brittonic is a form of Insular Celtic, which is descended from Proto-\nCeltic, a hypothetical parent language that by the first half of the first\nmillennium BC was already diverging into separate dialects or\nlanguages. There is some evidence\nthat the Pictish language may have had close ties to Common Brittonic and could\nin fact be a fifth branch. Forsyth, Katherine, Language in\nPictland : the case against \"non-Indo-European Pictish\" (Utrecht: de Keltische\nDraak, 1997), 27.\n\nEvidence from Welsh shows a great influence from Latin on Common Brittonic\nduring the Roman period, and especially so in terms related to the Church and\nChristianity, which are nearly all Latin derivatives. Common Brittonic was later replaced in most of Scotland\nby Gaelic and south of the Firth of Forth also by Old English (which later\ndeveloped into the Scots language). Common Brittonic survived into the Middle\nAges in Southern Scotland and Cumbriaâsee Cumbric. Common Brittonic was\ngradually replaced by English throughout England; in the north, Cumbric\ndisappeared as late as the 13th century and, in the south, Cornish was\neffectively a dead language by the 19th century, although attempts to revitalize\nit have met with some success. Cornwall Council, 2010-12-07.\n[http://www.cornwall.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=26766 UNESCO classes Cornish as a\nlanguage in the âprocess of revitalizationâ]. Retrieved 2011-01-13.\nO'Rahilly's historical model suggests the possibility that there was a Brythonic\nlanguage in Ireland before the arrival of Goidelic languages there, but this\nview has not found wide acceptance.\n","linknr":379,"url":"Common_Brittonic","recorded":1374761048,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Common_Brittonic&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Common_Brittonic&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Brythonic_languages","/wiki/Great_Britain","/wiki/Firth_of_Forth","/wiki/Extinct_language","/wiki/Old_Welsh","/wiki/Cumbric_language","/wiki/Cornish_language","/wiki/Breton_language","/wiki/Language_family","/wiki/Indo-European_languages","/wiki/Celtic_languages","/wiki/Insular_Celtic_languages","/wiki/Brythonic_languages","/wiki/ISO_639-3","http://multitree.linguistlist.org/codes/1bd","/wiki/Linguasphere_Observatory","/wiki/P-Celtic_and_Q-Celtic_languages","/wiki/Great_Britain","/wiki/Britons_(historical)","/wiki/Brythonic_languages","/wiki/Welsh_language","/wiki/Cumbric","/wiki/Cornish_language","/wiki/Bret